🔹 What is inspect?

inspect is a method that returns a developer-friendly string representation of an object.

It is mainly used for:

Debugging

Console output (IRB / Rails console)

p method

🔎 Basic Example
"hello".inspect

Output:

"\"hello\""

Notice:

It includes quotes

It shows the real internal representation

Compare with to_s:

"hello".to_s

Output:

"hello"

No extra formatting.

🔹 Key Difference: to_s vs inspect
Method	Purpose	Output Style
to_s	User-friendly display	Clean
inspect	Developer/debug display	Raw + detailed
🔥 Why p Uses inspect

When you write:

p "hello"

Ruby internally does:

puts "hello".inspect

That’s why you see:

"hello"
🔹 Example with Array
arr = [1,2,3]
puts arr

Output:

1
2
3

Because puts calls to_s.

Now:

p arr

Output:

[1, 2, 3]

Because p calls inspect.

🔹 Example with nil
puts nil

(blank line)

p nil
nil

inspect makes debugging easier.

🔹 Custom inspect (Very Important)

You can override inspect in your own class.

class User
  def initialize(name, age)
    @name = name
    @age = age
  end

  def inspect
    "User(name: #{@name}, age: #{@age})"
  end
end

u = User.new("Shubham", 25)
p u

Output:

User(name: Shubham, age: 25)

Now debugging becomes clean.

🔹 Where Ruby Automatically Uses inspect

p

IRB / Rails console

When printing objects inside arrays or hashes

String interpolation sometimes in debugging

Example:

u = User.new("Shubham", 25)
[ u ]

Ruby uses inspect to show it.

🔥 Internally

Every Ruby object inherits inspect from:

Object

Default version prints:

#<ClassName:0x00007ff...>

Example:

class A; end
p A.new

Output:

#<A:0x00007f...>

That comes from default inspect.

🎯 Simple Definition (Interview Style)

inspect returns a string containing a detailed, developer-friendly representation of an object, mainly used for debugging.

